{"id":"1608.02122","submitter":"Ayan Banerjee","authors":"Sudipta K. Bera, Avinash Kumar, Souvik Sil, Tushar Kanti Saha, Tanumoy\n  Saha, and Ayan Banerjee","title":"Simultaneous measurement of mass and rotation of trapped absorbing\n  particles in air","comments":"5 pgs, 3 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1364/OL.41.004356","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.soft physics.optics","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We trap absorbing micro-particles in air by photophoretic forces generated\nusing a single loosely focused Gaussian trapping beam. We measure a component\nof the radial Brownian motion of a trapped particle cluster and determine the\npower spectral density, mean squared displacement, and normalized position and\nvelocity autocorrelation functions in order to characterize the photophoretic\nbody force in a quantitative fashion for the first time. The trapped particles\nalso undergo spontaneous rotation due to the action of this force. This is\nevident from the spectral density that displays clear peaks at the rotation and\nthe particles' inertial resonance frequencies. We fit the spectral density to\nthe well-known analytical function derived from the Langevin equation, measure\nthe resonance and rotation frequencies and determine values for particle mass\nthat we verify at different trapping laser powers with reasonable accuracy.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 6 Aug 2016 15:58:13 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 29 Aug 2016 12:05:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-11-03"}
{"id":"1608.02427","submitter":"Harald Kr\\\"oll","authors":"Harald Kroll, Matthias Korb, Benjamin Weber, Samuel Willi and Qiuting\n  Huang","title":"Maximum-Likelihood Detection for Energy-Efficient Timing Acquisition in\n  NB-IoT","comments":"5 pages, 6 figures, submitted to M2M Communications and the Internet\n  of Things workshop at WCNC 2017","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.NI","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Initial timing acquisition in narrow-band IoT (NB-IoT) devices is done by\ndetecting a periodically transmitted known sequence. The detection has to be\ndone at lowest possible latency, because the RF-transceiver, which dominates\ndownlink power consumption of an NB-IoT modem, has to be turned on throughout\nthis time. Auto-correlation detectors show low computational complexity from a\nsignal processing point of view at the price of a higher detection latency. In\ncontrast a maximum likelihood cross-correlation detector achieves low latency\nat a higher complexity as shown in this paper. We present a hardware\nimplementation of the maximum likelihood cross-correlation detection. The\ndetector achieves an average detection latency which is a factor of two below\nthat of an auto-correlation method and is able to reduce the required energy\nper timing acquisition by up to 34%.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 5 Aug 2016 16:24:10 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 7 Oct 2016 10:42:26 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 23 Nov 2016 08:55:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-11-24"}
